This paper involves extensive outdoor measurements of wireless channels at 28 GHz, which is a key frequency band for 5G networks. The focus is on achieving adequate coverage with high gain antennas, which is a topic of interest in the fields of information theory (cs.IT) and network infrastructure (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of power-law models to represent the path gain-distance dependence, which is a common approach in the field of millimeter-wave communications (cs.MM). Additionally, the paper involves the use of specialized equipment to emulate a base station, which is relevant to the field of mobile computing (cs.MA). Finally, the paper discusses the issue of azimuth gains being degraded through scattering, which is a topic of interest in the field of control systems (cs.SY).
